Hi everyone!

Here is another game in GM Cyrano's MT where I have been playing against the big boys this time a Master with a rating close to IM level.  I end up in a position where I have a rook against 2 pieces.  Boy those two pieces proved to be much more lethal than a rook.  In fact all black's remaining pieces swarmed around Henry who sadly got stung and suffered an anaphylactic shock.  So how did this happen.  Well before I start here is the gameknot analysis: http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17836549&rnd=0.9027691620956812
1. .... e6 - this is the French Defense.  At first sight it appears cramping but this can cause the white player to overplay his or her hand later on.
3. ..... exd5 - exchange variation.
6. Nc3 - both sides concentrate on piece development.
9. 0-0 - and Henry tucks himself away on the kingside.  Alas this will be where Henry will meet his doom later on.
10. ..... Nbxd5 - this pawn could not be sustained.  Things are gonna start hotting up over the next few moves.
12. ...... Nxd5 - knight trade.
13. Qf3 - hitting out at the knight on d5 and Glenda is also fixing her beady eye on f7.
14. Bc4 - pin and another piece attacks f7.
17. ...... Kxf7 - so after a tactical melee over the last few moves we have a position of R and P v 2 pieces.  My position does not look too bad at the mo - but ..... a few moves down the line .....
20. ...... Bg4 ..... it will.  The swarm now begins.
21. a3? - Gameknot Analysis thought that b4 was better giving up a pawn but freeing myself from the bind I am currently in.
24. b4 - three moves too late.
26. .... Rg8 - now comes the black rook.
28. ..... Rh4+ - deadly Henry has only one square to go.
29. ..... Bf2 MATE!! - Henry is fatally stung by black's dsb on f2.  This is awesome guys!

Strange decision to play this move. For instance all white has to do is to capture on c4 with the bishop and he has already the threat Qb3. The light squared bishop is poorly placed. In this opening we will see that simply following the fundamental(and mistakenly called "beginner" or "basic") principles we can find the BEST move in each of the positions quickly. Here black should have played ...Nf6 getting the least active piece. I should also note that without any calculation this move is not best The bishop was already active so we shouldn't move it again.
It's a necessary move to make. Now white should simply castle or play Nc3 but we can also do the move h3 which should be best putting the question to the bishop.

Perhaps castling will put white under an annoying pin but it is only annoying. White probably will not even care if ...Bxf3 ruins the structure since he will be getting bishop pair open file for the rook and a boost in center control. It will suit him fine.

Once again we should have simply played with the least active piece Nf6. Really we can find the best moves in one second if we just use the base principles. Who knows maybe this bishop would like to go to e7. In that case there is an issue of flexibility as well.
Once again the most active forward move is Nc3 so we should simply do it.
Black has played a good opening but his pieces are not the best in placement and are a bit vulnerable. However we have seen a simple modest development of forces so we cannot make a real criticism.

White now needed to play the move of 8.e4 with a good position. If the move of e5 gets to happen a piece will be lost and white will have a permanent space advantage in the kingside(at least for the whole middlegame good for an attack). Not only that black could not even have played move of 8...e5 9.dxe5 Bxe5 10.Bxf7+ and white is simply winning. I should also mention that the move e4 would free the dark squares bishop.
Now black has a great game since white has not taken the key moment. He already has a threat.

I would not have played this move. It weakens the kingside light squares and is just making too great of a concession on the kingside. At least if a kingside weakening is called for play h3 instead and Bh2+ gives black nothing.
Good idea and black already has snatched opening edge at the very least equality.
We should not move the pieces twice when we should develop. In fact white should still sieze the chance of e4 with a good game still. Here black can safely answer with e5.

Not the best move. It has a clear idea to stop the white development of his dark squared bishop but white can easily stop the idea. He should have simply played Nbd7 then considered a choice break move of e5 probably but c5 could also be possible in some lines.
White needs to move his piece again to free himself and the move is actually not so bad.

When there is a contact between the pieces we should keep it up unless it gives us a real tactic. Usually releasing the tension gives the opponent activity. Now black has lost his defensive knight on the kingside while white has freed himself nicely. Black should have played Nbd7.
It fails to a tactical shot which to white's credit he finds. Many players rated in that area would not be able to find the move.
The only move and black is now having a major disadvantage in both lines.
Even worse for black would have been 13...Kh8 14.Ng5

And now we get a very important lesson. If you have a good winning move that gives you great advantage and an unclear line(Of course the unclear line is just losing) that simply take the great advantage. I suppose that white expected the move ...Rc8. If white checks it is actually not so clear anymore and white needs to do a SERIOUS calculation. White should simply capture the bishop.
Of course there is the defense
I don't think the rest of the game needed an annotation-Black slowly converted his advantage.
This is by far the longest game to annotate but it has so many instructive points and is a perfect game between 2 "average" rated players on this site.
Black is playing his queen out too early so white can immediately attack it. The Scandinavian Defense is OK but 2...Nf6 is more fundamentally sound.

Typical book line? It is but in the opening we should worry ourselves with the development of the pieces and not play moves like this. Black is simply trying to stall his development but create a sort of position in which white cannot use the development. It is not a fully correct idea and is very difficult to implement since the attack is easier to play for white and black's defense needs to be more carefully played.  3...Nf6 was my best choice.
Again we should have played 5...Nf6 playing a move that MUST be played sooner or later.
White breaks the pin. A fine move but all he needed to do was 6.h3 and followed with 7.g4 kicking the bishop off. Since white has more development it easily compensates for his weaknesses.

To be honest although this breaks the principles it is actually a decent idea that is in many scandinavian lines. The purpose is to control the b4 square and prevent the black queen and bishop from using it. Also white may play b4 in some lines. I probably would have just castled.
Good move for white an attacking move so he should put it on high priority.

This move is definitely a poor one. As we can see the d6 bishop is the good bishop and it also controls the black's weak dark squares. So now white should take the opportunity and grab the bishop getting an even bigger advantage in the line---10.Nxd6 Qxd6 11.b3 followed by a4 and now the black's weak dark squares will be under the attack. White has a clear advantage here.

White fails to take the opportunity and now his advantage has become very little. One of the best ways to get a good position is to trade your knight for the opponent's bishop especially in the open and dynamic pawn structures. A bishop's activity is by far the most ranged of the pieces. Sometimes it is a big pawn with a hat but at others it is almost equaling a rook in power(13B/14R maximum controls). In the open position bishops are favored but in dynamic structures we can now work on creating a favorable pawn structure.
Good idea for white to activate his pawns and they will give him good space.

This choice is very risky and I really don't like it too much. It may not be so bad but white has the c4 and d4 pawns attacking towards the queenside. If white can quickly get his queenside attack in black is in big trouble. Certainly a kingside castling was much safer.

This pawn move lets go of the nice square d5. However it is not bad. White is gaining more space on the queenside and fixing the b7 pawn. Secondly he is forcing the dark squared bishop to an exchange which will weaken the dark squares or to go backwards where it is weaker. White intends to follow with b4 and b5.

Another instructive mistake by black. White gets a clear advantage now. 
Black has traded a key bishop for a weaker knight and his dark squares are so weak after hxg3 and Bf4. White's attack obviously comes first.

Very strange. White's intention is to activate his rook immediately but in these types of position it is almost always right to take with the h pawn. Firstly white would need serious justification to weaken the central squares and a major endgame disadvantage. Also white is attacking on the queenside so this makes no sense. Much better was hxg3. However at least white takes back the piece and this mistake is not as serious as the black's last move.

Black immediately takes control of the weak square. There is a major problem--It fails tactically. The black queen has only a5 as a safe square and after b4 it will be trapped. So after Bf4 black is in big trouble. That is why ...Nd5 was the best move with a advantage for white but a complex position.
Now white is just winning.
Black is losing a lot of material. There is the attack on g4 as well as a discovery.
Black could not save the piece with 17...Qe7 18.Qxe4 f6 19.Qg4+
OK. So white is a full bishop up and should be winning? Yes but the technical grind is very instructive.

This is a huge mistake for sure. When losing black needed to play R2e3 and that would avoid the trades. Now everything is easy for white. He will lose one pawn but he has no more problems. By the way black was losing in either line but we should still put up max resistance.
Another trade makes things easy.
Black's king is active but it is not very useful. White's idea now is to fix the black pawns on the dark squares.
White simply needed to take EP and he has a majority and pawws pawn. That would be the easiest win. Now things actually get interesting.
White's pawns are fixed on the dark squares and black the opposite. This is not what white wants.

And now if black had the ability to pass and not move he would have a draw in this posiiton! Black just needs to put the pawn on a6 keep the king on e6 and he automatically draws! However white can now force the king back with zugswang.
White is using the bishop to "pass" in the position.
!!!??? A very strange idea. White only has to use the king to play 29.Ke5 and the win goes easily. If black takes the bishop then he loses both pawns on the kingside.
White simply wasted time.
White finds the right way to win.
So now the win is trivial.
Black now resigns-A very interesting game.
Reverse Sicilian is one I enjoy as it can play mind games for black and gives different options to white with the extra tempo.

Funny thing is that I immediately try to remove the imbalance of the Sicilian style opening. Removing imbalance as in trying to disrupt opposite dominant sides of the board per player. I see the Sicilian as having good chances for both players.
Kingside! I had a feeling he would play for the kingside as he previously did in the last blitz game.
I think 3. ...e4 is an interesting idea.
Not much so far.
white may lose a tempo to castle. I think Be2 is a safer move for white.
?? This move feels so natural but is so wrong. Black hangs his own pawn and is underdeveloped.
Taking the pawn and threatening the bishop. Black should simply move his bishop out of harm's way and accept a less than ideal position.
?? Another bad move spells a disadvantage for black.
! and now white has a pretty clear victory as black cannot defend the bishop. His a8 rook may also be killed along with the c7 pawn. White just has so many options of obtaining an advantage.

It's an interesting game I played some time ago actually. Once players start to realize that the queen is worth a limited amount of wood(minor pieces/rooks) their evaluation of that piece drop significantly. However the queen can still dominate the pieces in many occasions. It happens when the greater number of pieces cannot coordinate.

I've actually seen this player use this setup in his other games. One big problem many players have is that they play the same opening setup against all openings even if it is not optimal. I remember that I used to always do the King's Indian Setup without thinking about the opponent. It's a horrible mistake many players make.
Of course to prevent the white knight from developing.
Bringing the queen out so early is usually not the best idea. Here it is definitely not best. White easily could have played Nf3 which is definitely going to be played at some point.

White is making already 4 pawn moves out of his 5 and is playing this opening kind of like a sicilian Kan variation. The unfortunate thiing is that black has the extra space in the center and has contact between the pawns so the pawn structure is dynamic and black can open it at the right moment. Since white has broken the principles of the opening black can also do it if he wants.
Creating of a weakness.
Now the c5 square is no longer controlled so the bishop goes there easily.

White wants to quickly close up the position where his lack of development will not be so bad. Black should open things up on the queenside because the center is impossible to open. I should say that even if the position would be completely closed up black would still be much better since the white's pieces are all misplaced.
Now black just has a clear advantage since he has accomplished the goals he wanted to.
Now there are more weaknesses in the white's position since he is advancing all his pawns up the board.

(!)If you check out most of my annotations I almost NEVER give exclamations to moves even if they are very good. However I was very proud to discover this move and the idea behind it. It simply looks like a blunder at first sight since white can gain material getting of the 2 rooks for queen. Howeverblack has a strong idea in mind. Definitely an exclamation.

Now white must go back and with the white queen gone there is no piece left to defend the hanging light squared weaknesses on b5 and a4. Now we notice that black can attack them immediately the c2 queen having disappeared. A great way to realize our plan.

Of course white has a light squared bishop which is good for defending the weaknesses but it is on the other side of the board. White cannot avoid losing his weaknesses since he has no piece that can guard them.

White will both of his queenside pawns and then black will have connected passed pawns  and they will win the game. At this point I was pretty sure the win was "in my pocket" and I started to play  moves very quickly without even thinking almost.

Black has realized the plan and now there is another one to advance the pawns to the 8th rank and get a queen. Although all of white's pieces are "developed" we see that his bishop pair is totally useless.
Black is simply realizing the plan.
Now black is getting more forces to the queenside where they will support the pawns.
Of course the knight could not be allowed on the f4 square.

This move now is really a blunder. I had playing my previous moves in only a few seconds and after playing this one a quick calculation made me realize that I had just blundered one of my passed pawns. Now I had to slow down and start being more careful. A real wake up! Instead black wins more material by force after 29...a4 when both of the white's bishops are suffocating.
Now I need to get complicated in order to regain my advantage.
White's bishop pair is gaining now in strength.
Now black is winning again but a good plan is needed. Black should support both passed pawns and advanced both of them.
Another good move. This one allows the queen to support the d pawn all the way to d1.
Now white has jsut made the blunder and stopping this pawn will cost him far too much.
The final mistake of the game but white was already losing.
Queens and passed pawns are working together very well.

Now white simply gave up. In conclusion the evaluation of the game shifted in my favor in the early stage then came back a bit to white but I managed to grab the wheel again and was back to a winning advantage. In the opening we should mainly use our general principles instead of mindlessly playing the easy setups.

My feeling is that g6 is a weak response as it immediately increases white's advantate with space development in the center and already defines your intentions on the kingside.  I would try a more open and active response to 1. e4 perhaps e5 or c5.
Notice how white is building control of the center.
Your dsB is locked in and the knight is alreaady constricted.

White is playing a conventional opening.  Check the database and you can see the usual moves that are played and consider why they are typical.  Why are you playing h6?  Your queenside pieces are not yet developed.
Your kingside is hemmed in.  White already has a major advantage in space activity and development.

Why the pawn move?  You need to develop your pieces.  Usually consider knights before bishops bishops before rooks etc.  Control of the center is important in the openings and middlegames.  Pawn moves are usually weak unless they enable development of your pieces.
Your queenside pieces are still hemmed in.  What is your plan to develop them and gain greater activity?
White is trying to figure out what to do.
Okay knight out.  This is good.  The game is in a precarious position at this point.  Much can be done to improve the opening position in subsequent games.  Additional comments are welcome by anyone.
d5 is good.

Why are you moving this pawn?  Generally you don't want to advance pawns unless you already have an advantage with pieces and activity.  My first objective in this position would be to gain equality and then after that to gain the initiative.
The knight move was allowed by the pawn advance.
Why moving f5?
It's a very tough position at this point.
